{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480503"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:44:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:44:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"59"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"59","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/59"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.16,0.64,0.08,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"59"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94400"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"59","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/59"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"59"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77438"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"136"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1412"},{"type":"tags","id":"3311"},{"type":"tags","id":"3382"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29124"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31383"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41973"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43781"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94400","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94400"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ETwo days following an elective endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP), sphincterotomy, and stone extraction for choledocholithiasis, a 55-year-old woman is reviewed after complaining of nausea and epigastric pain. Her symptoms started four hours earlier. The operation note records that the procedure was prolonged due to difficulty with manipulation around the papillary orifice. The patient is feeling unwell and has a pulse rate of 96/min, blood pressure 114/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, and temperature of 37.8C. She has some epigastric tenderness but the abdomen is generally soft.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chest X-ray","Upper abdominal ultrasound","Serum lipase","CT abdomen and pelvis","Septic screen"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst generally considered a safe and effective diagnostic and therapeutic procedure, endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) does have its associated complications. It is estimated that somewhere between 6% and 10% of patients undergoing ERCP will have one such complication and in half these cases the complication is acute pancreatitis. Other complications include, cholangitis, haemorrhage and duodenal perforation. Pancreatitis is typically a complication of extensive biliary or pancreatic manipulation and the post-procedure rates in such circumstances can be as high as 30%. Injection of contrast into the pancreatic duct, difficult cannulation, and failure of stone clearance can be associated with this increased risk. It is very likely that this patient\u0027s current situation would be explained by this complication. Estimation of the \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum lipase\u003C/strong\u003E will provide a rapid confirmation of such a diagnosis. The serum lipase elevates some 3 - 6 hours after onset of an episode of pancreatitis and will peak at 24 hours. Whilst it might not reach absolute diagnostic levels early, in the situation described in this case, virtually any elevation in the serum lipase levels will support a diagnosis of pancreatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf there was any diagnostic doubt, a \u003Cstrong\u003Echest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E could be performed looking for free intra-abdominal gas. If this X-ray was unhelpful, further imaging (\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan\u003C/strong\u003E) could be considered. It is unlikely that an \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is going to be of any diagnostic value. \u003Cstrong\u003ESepsis\u003C/strong\u003E is a possible explanation for the current picture, but pancreatitis is a more likely diagnosis and should be excluded first.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A patient becoming unwell within a few days of an ERCP is most likely to have had a complication related to that procedure."],"references":["Szary NM, Al-Kawas FH. Complications of Endoscopic Retrograde Cholangiopancreatography: How to Avoid and Manage Them. Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2013; 9:496-504. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24719597/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77438"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"59"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77438"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-23T21:29:11+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T21:29:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"59"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94400"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","lin